1
00:00:03,031 --> 00:00:07,277
A radiation machine gave one patient roughly 100 times the intended dose.

2
00:00:08,259 --> 00:00:10,343
The manufacturer said it was impossible.

3
00:00:11,224 --> 00:00:12,105
Then it happened again.

4
00:00:12,147 --> 00:00:17,555
The Therac-25 replaced physical safety interlocks with software checks.

5
00:00:18,436 --> 00:00:27,132
During fast data entry, a race condition could leave the machine in the wrong state and fire a full power beam with no filter.

6
00:00:27,111 --> 00:00:33,304
Nobody caught it because the code had been reused from older machines, and reused code felt like tested code.

7
00:00:34,246 --> 00:00:35,710
Operators reported errors.

8
00:00:36,610 --> 00:00:39,838
The manufacturer insisted the machine was safe.

9
00:00:39,936 --> 00:00:43,146
More patients were burned before the pattern was treated as real.

10
00:00:43,185 --> 00:00:46,215
The disaster was not just bad code.

11
00:00:46,896 --> 00:00:54,459
It was a system with no independent safety layer, no quick way to believe field reports, and no design for software being wrong.

12
00:00:55,601 --> 00:00:59,412
That is how small causes become massive consequences.
